<TITLE> Businessman, friend of ex-NSI chief, quizzed in 10 truck arms case </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Chittagong, Oct 22 (bdnews24.com)The Criminal Investigation Department on Thursday quizzed an associate of the former director general of National Security Intelligence in connection with the bid to smuggle 10 truckloads of arms into Bangladesh in 2004. Investigation officer of the case, the CID's Moniruzzaman Chowdhury, said businessman Syed Mahmudul Huq was questioned for four hours at the agency's Dampara office. Police seized 10 trucks of weapons and ammunition on April 1, 2004, as the arms consignment was being offloaded at Chittagong Urea Fertiliser Ltd jetty. The CID has questioned around 80 persons in this connection over the last 20 months, since investigations were reopened in the case. So far seven people have been arrestedfive officers of NSI including two of its former chiefsand former managing director and general manager of CUFL. "The arrestee (Huq) was summoned to the CID office as he is a close friend of former NSI director general retired brigadier general Abdur Rahim," said Chowdhury. Huq appeared at the CID office at 10am and was questioned for four hours. He might be called again, the investigation officer said. bdnews
